msContents.summary: Three works bound together and copied in different hands. The first is a collection of moral anecdotes; the second is a short work on Islamic practice regarding women also known as Kuls̲ūm nanah (or Kuls̲ūmʹnanah); it contains an introduction, 15 chapters and a conclusion; the third is an unidentified leaf summarizing rules regarding men and women.

title: Hāz̲ā kitāb Sirāj al-munīr. ʻAqāyid al-nisā.

title.#text: هذا کتاب سراج المنير. عقايد النسا

layoutDesc.layout: First work written in 10 long lines; second work in 20 long lines; third work in 14 long lines.

scriptDesc.scriptNote: Written in nastaʻlīq in black ink; pointed.

decoNote: First page border-ruled in red; some rubrications in red.

origin.p: The second item is dated 1241 A.H. (f. 146v) the first item was likely copied at a similar time.

provenance: Gift of Professor A. Yohannan, Nov. 18, 1913 (note in pencil, f. 1r).
Formerly owned by Abraham Yohannan (note in pencil, f. 1r; library donation plate inside front cover).

term: Muslim women--Conduct of life--Early works to 1800
